[Note that the case definition proposed by CDC for this syndrome includes a history of COVID-19 which may influence the proportion of cases with history of COVID-19, and limits the age of presentation to less than 21 years of age. I suspect that like following the 1st announcement of this syndrome, we may move from a "don't look and it isn't there" surveillance in young adults to a "seek and ye shall find" surveillance.

The statement re: Internal Medicine specialists who treat young adults when they "outgrow" their pediatricians age wise, haven't seen many if any cases of Kawasaki disease is quite true (I am an internist by training) so this may have been missed. It does seem fit on the spectrum of hyper-immune inflammatory responses seen in some of adult patients with severe COVID-19, just some differences leaning more to a Kawasaki-like presentation. As the healthcare providers start looking, it would not be surprising if more cases are identified in young adults.

As more cases are identified, hopefully there will be some more answers to what exactly is going on, and what most effective therapies should be implemented. - Mod.MPP

