[As more physicians are looking, more cases are being identified. And now, with the information on the Washington Post article (item [2] above), I suspect we will learn of more young adults (and possibly not so young adults), who may fit the clinical profile.

The publication by Belhadjer et al (item [5] above) is a case series of 35 children with acute heart failure, fitting the CDC criteria for multisystem inflammatory syndrome in children -- MIS-C (also referred to as pediatric multisystem inflammatory syndrome -- PMIS) in France and Switzerland. Thus far there have not been fatalities reported in this group of 35 children, but long term sequelae have not been ruled out yet. The authors noted high levels of brain natriuretic peptide (BNP) in the series of patients and suggested the process was not due to inflammatory myocardial arteritis but rather myocardial edema or stunning. In their discussion, the authors mentioned they implemented a protocol for Emergency Room evaluations of pediatric patients presenting with prolonged and unexplained fever with a rapid N- terminal pro b-type natriuretic peptide (NTproBNP), even in the absence of cardiac involvement. In the 3 weeks following implementation of this protocol, they saw an increase in patients with less severe forms of disease presenting without heart failure and some with heart failure but without the need for mechanical assistance.

While cases haven't been reported from Wuhan, China, (the 1st "hot spot"), perhaps a look back to see if there was an increase in Kawasaki diagnoses during and following the high COVID-19 activity in the City, although the cumulative documented clinical cases were less than those seen in European and North American hot spots, and in other Asian countries (including Japan), where Kawasaki disease is known to occur more frequently than in Western countries.

As is mentioned above, the SARS-CoV-2 continues to provide us with surprises.... - Mod.MPP

